# DOM Day 8 - Updating and Deleting Elements

## Topics Learned
- Updating Elements
- Removing Elements
- remove()
- display = "none"
- Multiple Event Listeners

---

## Update Text

```javascript
document.querySelector("#message").innerText =
"Welcome to AI Healthcare App";
```

Updates the text of an existing element.

---

## Remove an Element

```javascript
document.querySelector("#message").remove();
```

Completely removes the element from the webpage.

---

## Hide vs Remove

Hide:

```javascript
document.querySelector("#message").style.display = "none";
```

- Element is hidden.
- Still exists in the DOM.

Remove:

```javascript
document.querySelector("#message").remove();
```

- Element is deleted from the DOM.
- It no longer exists on the page.

---

## Example

```javascript
let updateBtn = document.querySelector("#updateBtn");

updateBtn.addEventListener("click", function() {
    document.querySelector("#message").innerText =
    "Welcome to AI Healthcare App";
});

let deleteBtn = document.querySelector("#deleteBtn");

deleteBtn.addEventListener("click", function() {
    document.querySelector("#message").remove();
});
```

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Missing `#` in `querySelector()`

Wrong:

```javascript
document.querySelector("message");
```

Correct:

```javascript
document.querySelector("#message");
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- `innerText` updates text.
- `remove()` deletes an element.
- `display = "none"` hides an element.
- Use different variable names for different buttons.
- Always use `#` when selecting an element by ID.

